<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1683,2000]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
HABITAT. Unlike other members of the genus, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Nikolski" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[672,853,1902,1927]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Laudakia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="erythrogaster">
<emphasis box="[672,853,1902,1927]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">L. erythrogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
avoids vertical slopes and rocky outcrops. Instead it is found on clayey and sandy substrates in areas up to 
<quantity box="[755,840,1939,1964]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="m" value="1800.0">1800 m</quantity>
wherever there are colonies of gerbils (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1841" box="[1283,1420,1939,1964]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Rhombomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1283,1420,1939,1964]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Rhombomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), whose burrows serve as retreats for the lizards (
<bibRefCitation author="Anderson, S. C." box="[684,862,1975,2000]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" refId="ref45318" refString="Anderson, S. C. (1999) The lizards of Iran. Society for the Study of Amphibians and Reptiles, Oxford, Ohio, 442 pp." type="book" year="1999">Anderson 1999</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
